#compdef cppfront
# =============================================================================
# cppfront — Herb Sutter's "personal experimental C++ Syntax 2
#            -> Syntax 1 compiler" — a C++ source-to-source
#            translator that compiles programs written in the
#            experimental "Cpp2" (C++2) syntax to standard
#            "Cpp1" (current C++) source code.  Cpp2 is Herb
#            Sutter's exploration of "what C++ could look like"
#            — a cleaner, safer C++ dialect with named
#            parameters, explicit `out` / `in` / `inout` /
#            `move` parameter modes, post-conditions, defaulted
#            null/bound/sign-comparison safety checks, and
#            mixed Cpp1/Cpp2 file support.
#            Distinguishing from clang, gcc, msvc, and other
#            C++ compilers by:
#              - Cpp2 SYNTAX EXPERIMENT — cppfront is NOT a
#                full C++ compiler; it's a SYNTAX TRANSLATOR.
#                A .cpp2 source file is parsed as Cpp2,
#                checked for safety, and emitted as standard
#                .cpp (Cpp1) source.  The user then compiles
#                the generated .cpp with their normal C++
#                compiler (gcc/clang/msvc).
#              - NAMED PARAMETERS WITH DIRECTION — Cpp2's
#                signature feature: function parameters are
#                declared with explicit directions:
#                  add: (in a: int, in b: int) -> int = a + b;
#                  swap: (inout x: T, inout y: T) = { ... }
#                  produce: (out result: int) = result = 42;
#                  consume: (move s: string) = { ... }
#                Distinct from C++'s implicit pass-by-value /
#                reference / rvalue-reference distinctions.
#              - DEFAULT SAFETY CHECKS — Cpp2 ENABLES BY
#                DEFAULT (disable with -no-*-checks flags):
#                  * null-pointer dereference checks
#                  * integer division-by-zero checks
#                  * subscript-out-of-range checks
#                  * mixed-sign comparison checks
#                Distinct from C++ which has all checks
#                opt-in.
#              - MIXED Cpp1/Cpp2 FILES — a .cpp2 file can
#                contain BOTH new Cpp2 syntax AND legacy Cpp1
#                code in the same source.  cppfront emits a
#                .cpp file with both translated.  Pure Cpp2-
#                only via `-pure-cpp2` flag.
#              - C++23 IMPORT STD INTEGRATION — `-import-std`
#                uses C++23's `import std;` module system;
#                `-include-std` falls back to #include all
#                std:: headers (compatible with older
#                compilers).
#              - SYNTAX 2 ARCHITECTURE — declarations follow
#                `name: type = value` form (postfix types):
#                  i: int = 0;                     // variable
#                  next: (i: int) -> int = i + 1;  // function
#                  Point: type = { x: int; y: int; };  // type
#                Distinct from C++'s prefix declarations
#                (`int i = 0;`).
#              - SAFE TYPE CONVERSIONS via `as` operator —
#                Cpp2's `value as Type` performs checked
#                conversion (raises if invalid).  `is` operator
#                tests type membership without converting.
#                  v: variant<int, string> = 42;
#                  if v is int { /* ... */ }
#                  i := v as int;
#              - POSTCONDITIONS via `post` — function
#                contracts at the postcondition site:
#                  divide: (a: int, b: int) -> int
#                    pre b != 0,
#                    post(result: int) result * b == a
#                  = a / b;
#              - NO MORE TYPENAME / NO MORE TEMPLATE
#                DECLARATIONS — Cpp2's templates infer
#                template parameters; no `typename T` /
#                `template<>` boilerplate.
#              - INTEROP WITH ALL EXISTING C++ — generated
#                .cpp files work with any C++23-conformant
#                compiler; existing C++ code can call into
#                cppfront-generated functions and vice versa.
#              - 16+ COMPILER FLAGS — control output filename,
#                debug emission, safety check disabling,
#                exception/RTTI configuration, cwd
#            Used by: C++ committee members + early adopters
#            evaluating "what C++ could be," ISO C++ committee
#            discussions about future syntax directions,
#            educational comparisons of C++'s evolution
#            possibilities, and as a reference implementation
#            of C++23-era language design + source-to-source
#            translation in C++.
#
# Author:  Herb Sutter (hsutter on GitHub) — Microsoft
#          Distinguished Engineer; ISO C++ Standards Committee
#          chair since 2002; author of "Exceptional C++"
#          series (3 books); founder of Cpp2 / cppfront
#          experimental project (2022-present).  License:
#          Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception.
# Source:  https://github.com/hsutter/cppfront
#          https://github.com/hsutter/cppfront/blob/main/source/cppfront.cpp
#          https://github.com/hsutter/cppfront/blob/main/source/to_cpp1.h
#          https://github.com/hsutter/cppfront/blob/main/source/common.h
#          Talks: Herb's CppCon keynotes (2021, 2022, 2023,
#          2024 — "Bjarne Stroustrup, my favorite mentor...
#          What if we made breaking-change Cpp2?")
# CLI:     source/cppfront.cpp + source/to_cpp1.h — uses
#          custom cmdline_processor (Herb's own minimal argv
#          parser).  Headline focus: the LANGUAGE itself
#          (Cpp2 syntax), not the argparse framework.
# Language: Cpp2 (a.k.a. C++2 / cppfront C++ Syntax 2).
#           Distinct from:
#              * C++23 / C++26 (standard C++; Cpp2 is an
#                EXPERIMENTAL alternative syntax for the same
#                semantics)
#              * Carbon (Google's separate-language C++
#                successor experiment; in our corpus as `carbon`)
#              * Circle (Sean Baxter's C++ extension; in our
#                corpus as well)
#              * Rust (entirely different memory model)
#              * D (different syntax + GC)
#           Cpp2 distinguishes itself by:
#              1. SAME C++ SEMANTICS, NEW SYNTAX — Cpp2
#                 compiles to C++; mechanical translation
#                 preserves semantics
#              2. NAMED PARAMETER DIRECTIONS (in/out/inout/move)
#              3. SAFETY-CHECKS BY DEFAULT — null/div-zero/
#                 subscript/sign checks enabled by default
#              4. POSTFIX DECLARATIONS — `name: type = value`
#              5. POSTCONDITIONS via `post`
#              6. SAFE TYPE CONVERSIONS via `as` / `is`
#              7. MIXED Cpp1/Cpp2 — incremental migration
#              8. NO TEMPLATE BOILERPLATE
#              9. HERB-SUTTER / ISO-C++ COMMITTEE PROVENANCE
#                 — author chairs the ISO C++ committee
#             10. PERSONAL EXPERIMENT NOT ISO C++ — Herb's
#                 explicit framing: "what C++ could be";
#                 INFLUENCES ISO discussion but is not itself
#                 a standardization proposal
# License: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception
# Status:  cppfront — 5,951+ stars on hsutter/cppfront; active
#          experimental development by Herb Sutter since 2022;
#          frequent CppCon talks + blog updates; no production
#          deployment (explicit "personal experiment"); used
#          for educational comparisons + ISO C++ committee
#          discussion catalyst.
