# WHY Cpp2 IS A DISTINCTIVE 100TH LANGUAGE:
#
#   1. ISO C++ COMMITTEE CHAIR'S PERSONAL EXPERIMENT — Cpp2
#      is authored by Herb Sutter, who has chaired the ISO C++
#      Standards Committee since 2002.  Sutter is the most
#      authoritative figure in C++ language design alive.
#      Cpp2 is his personal experiment — "what C++ could be"
#      if we could redesign the syntax without backward-
#      compatibility constraints.  Unique authorial provenance
#      in the language taxonomy.
#
#   2. SOURCE-TO-SOURCE TRANSLATION ARCHITECTURE — Cpp2 isn't
#      a separate language with its own runtime / ABI; it's a
#      SYNTAX EXPERIMENT that emits standard C++.  The
#      cppfront compiler parses .cpp2, performs safety checks,
#      and emits .cpp.  Distinct from:
#         - C++ (Cpp2 IS a syntax for C++ semantics, not
#                Cpp1 itself)
#         - Carbon (Google's C++ successor — separate ABI)
#         - Rust (entirely different memory model)
#      Sutter's design constraint: "same semantics, new
#      syntax."  Whatever Cpp2 does, it must mechanically
#      translate to standard C++.
#
#   3. NAMED PARAMETER DIRECTIONS — Cpp2's signature
#      feature.  Function parameters declared with explicit
#      direction modes:
#         add: (in a: int, in b: int) -> int = a + b;
#         swap: (inout x: T, inout y: T) = {
#             tmp := x; x = y; y = tmp;
#         }
#         produce: (out result: int) = result = 42;
#         consume: (move s: string) = { ... }
#      The four modes:
#         in    — read-only (auto-detects pass-by-value /
#                  const-ref based on type)
#         out   — produce-only (uninitialized on entry,
#                  required initialized on return)
#         inout — read-write (pass-by-reference)
#         move  — consume (auto-moves out of caller)
#      Distinct from C++'s implicit pass-by-value /
#      pass-by-reference distinctions.
#
#   4. SAFETY CHECKS BY DEFAULT — Cpp2 ENABLES the following
#      runtime safety checks by default (disable explicitly):
#         * Null-pointer dereferences  (-no-null-checks)
#         * Integer division by zero    (-no-div-zero-checks)
#         * Subscript out-of-range      (-no-subscript-checks)
#         * Mixed-sign comparisons      (-no-comparison-checks)
#      Distinct from C++ where all checks are opt-in.  This
#      reflects Sutter's emphasis on safety-by-default
#      ("don't pay for what you use unless you opt out").
#
#   5. POSTFIX DECLARATIONS — Cpp2 syntax: `name: type =
#      value`.  Distinct from C++'s prefix syntax `type name
#      = value`:
#         Cpp2:  i: int = 0;
#         Cpp1:  int i = 0;
#         Cpp2:  next: (i: int) -> int = i + 1;
#         Cpp1:  auto next(int i) -> int { return i + 1; }
#      Postfix is unambiguous (no most-vexing parse) and
#      easier to extend with parameter modes.
#
#   6. POSTCONDITIONS via `post` — contract programming:
#         divide: (a: int, b: int) -> int
#           pre b != 0,
#           post(result: int) result * b == a
#         = a / b;
#      Contracts run at function exit; allow tools to reason
#      about correctness.
#
#   7. SAFE TYPE CONVERSIONS via `as` / `is` — Cpp2's `as`
#      operator performs CHECKED type conversion; `is` tests
#      type membership.  Distinct from C++'s `static_cast` /
#      `dynamic_cast` / C-style casts:
#         v: variant<int, string> = 42;
#         if v is int { i := v as int; }
#
#   8. MIXED Cpp1/Cpp2 FILES — a single .cpp2 file can
#      contain BOTH Cpp2 syntax AND legacy Cpp1 code; cppfront
#      emits a single .cpp file with both.  Enables
#      incremental migration: rewrite one function at a time
#      to Cpp2 syntax while keeping the rest as standard C++.
#
#   9. C++23 import std INTEGRATION — Cpp2 takes advantage of
#      C++23's module system via `-import-std` flag, or falls
#      back to `#include <...>` via `-include-std` for older
#      compilers.
#
#  10. EDUCATIONAL CATALYST — Cpp2 has driven significant ISO
#      C++ committee discussion about future syntax
#      directions.  Sutter's CppCon keynotes (2021-2024) on
#      Cpp2 reach hundreds of thousands of C++ developers.
#      Even if Cpp2 itself never becomes ISO C++, it
#      influences which features the ISO committee considers
#      for C++26 / C++29.
